1.text: Note that you have monolid eyes if your eyelid doesn’t have a crease.

2.text: Figure out if you have hooded eyes by examining the crease, if you have one.

3.text: Study the tilt of your eyes to figure out if they are upturned or downturned.

4.text: Note that you have almond eyes if you can’t see white around the iris.

5.text: Recognize that you have round eyes if you can see white below your iris.

6.text: Measure the gap between your eyes to determine if they are wide- or close-set.

7.text: Examine the depth of your eyes to determine if they are deep-set or prominent.

8.text: Compare your eyes with your nose and mouth size to figure out your eye size.

9.text: Create a gradient of eye-shadow for monolid eyes.

10.text: Extend eye shadow beyond the crease for hooded eyes.

11.text: Emphasize the tilt of upturned eyes with smokey eyeshadow.

12.text: Try a cat-eye look for downturned eyes.

13.text: Add length to round, small, or deep-set eyes with a gradient of eyeshadow.

14.text: Extend close-set eyes with smokey shadow to emphasize the outer corners.

15.text: Try a halo look for almond eyes.

16.text: Put dark eyeshadow and liner on the inner corners of wide set eyes.

17.text: Use darker shadow for large or protruding eyes.
